The not-so-good: There were 3 tables filled in the whole place but our food still seemed to take awhile. A tad too pricey for what it is, $12 was too much. The presentation of the food itself was pretty poor, especially for dining in. Gryo came out still in the wrapper and the fries in a cardboard carrier. Fine for to-go or at a stadium, not so much on a plate...  Atmosphere: 8/10 Service: 8.5/10 Food: 8.5/10

I knew this restaurant is small, but I didn't think it would be that small. Although their website says they cannot accommodate a party greater than 6, I wouldn't suggest coming here with more than 4. There were 3 tables that can fit 4 people, about 6 for duos, and the rest were bar seatings.  I arrived here with the husband at 5:12pm on a Sunday and it was completely full. We were quoted a wait time of about 45 minutes. Wait, didn't this place just open a few minutes ago? Weird. Perhaps it is their very popular happy hour special ($12 for half a dozen of selected oysters and a crafted beer) that gets everyone here early. The happy hour lasts from 5pm-7pm and is every day of the week. I wouldn't normally wait this long to eat at a restaurant but I've bookmarked this place for a while now and was set on coming here. Anyway, true to their estimation, the hostess texted us shortly before 6pm to say our table is ready.  We ordered one happy hour special, the crab cakes as an appetizer, and for entrees: the fettuccine with clams and the scallops with mushroom risotto.  I am not going to act like I know much about oysters because they all taste the same to me after I top it with my beloved horseradish and cocktail sauce, but they tasted fresh and were served with the quickness.  To me, the real winner were the crab cakes. Oh my the crab cakes! The outer portion of the crab cake has a delicate crunch while the inside is filled with crabby deliciousness. I love it when you can really taste the sweetness of the crab. The arugula salad it came with was drizzled with a spicy honey dressing and was just wow. I never thought a honey dressing would work but it sure did. That appetizer was no doubt the highlight of the entire meal and I highly recommend it.  Mmm. When the scallops entree was served, the aroma of the ocean immediately hit my nose. The scallops were perfectly seared on the outside with a nice salty crisp while the inside were buttery soft and just melts in your mouth. I thought the mushroom risotto really tied the whole dish together really well.  Of everything, I found the fettuccine with clams to be a let down. While I thought the clams were deliciously garlicky and plentiful, the pasta itself was mediocre. Even with the cheese mixed in well, I found the pasta to be lacking in flavor and just plain oily. The pasta was also slightly overdone for my liking.  We received complimentary whiskey cake when we asked for our check, which is always a nice touch. I love free stuff! While the whiskey cake had great flavors, it was so dry that I felt like I could've choked on it.  Overall, I thought the food here is really good although I don't see myself coming back as it was not necessarily life-changing. Plus it is not worth the long wait especially in LES where there is a great restaurant in every corner. Prices are very reasonable. Nonetheless if you have time to spare to wait around and love seafood, this may be a place worth checking out.

Thoroughly mediocre.  We order from Pita Heaven every now and then (mainly because it's convenient, not because of the quality), so I feel like l have a pretty good sample size.  If you order any sort of "plate" they will give you a salad with iceberg lettuce at the bottom, but a few piece of higher quality greens on top to make you think it is a higher quality salad.  Then, they douse it with too much salad dressing, and the salad dressing runs throughout the bottom of the carryout container and seeps into the rest of your meal.  I wish they would either put the salad in a separate container or use a different kind of container so that the salad dressing doesn't ruin the rest of my meal.  With respect to the entrees, I usually get a gyros plate, because that is typically the hardest thing to screw up (try as they might).  It's not the highest quality gyros meat, and it's usually overcooked, but at least it's usually edible.  Don't waste your money on the "Greek fries".  They're just regular fries (often soggy and undercooked), with about 20 cents worth of feta cheese and some oregano.  They're certainly not worth the $1.50 up-charge as a side item with your plate.  Basically, if you really want a gyros, but you're too lazy to go to Greek town, this is acceptable.  But if you're looking for high quality food, which is consistent with the price point being charged, you may want to take a pass.
